Step 1: Create DynamoDB Table
Go to AWS Console → Search DynamoDB

Click Create table

Table name: S3Files

Partition key: unique

Key type: String

Leave all other defaults

Click Create table

Wait for status to change from "Creating" to "Active" (10-20 seconds)

Part B: Create S3 Bucket
Step 1: Create S3 Bucket
Go to AWS Console → Search S3

Click Create bucket

Bucket name: malleshaishu (or your unique name)

Region: us-east-1

Uncheck "Block all public access" (if needed)

Click Create bucket

Part C: Create Lambda Function
Step 1: Create Lambda Function
Go to AWS Console → Search Lambda

Click Create function

Choose Author from scratch

Function name: S3ToDynamo

Runtime: Python 3.9 (or 3.14)

Architecture: x86_64

Click Create function

Step 2: Write Lambda Code
Scroll down to Code source section

Replace the existing code with:

python
import boto3
from uuid import uuid4

def lambda_handler(event, context):
    print("Lambda function started")
    
    dynamodb = boto3.resource('dynamodb')
    dynamoTable = dynamodb.Table('S3Files')
    
    if 'Records' in event:
        for record in event['Records']:
            bucket_name = record['s3']['bucket']['name']
            object_key = record['s3']['object']['key']
            size = record['s3']['object'].get('size', -1)
            event_name = record.get('eventName', 'Unknown')
            event_time = record.get('eventTime', 'Unknown')
            
            dynamoTable.put_item(
                Item={
                    'unique': str(uuid4()),
                    'Bucket': bucket_name,
                    'Object': object_key,
                    'Size': size,
                    'Event': event_name,
                    'EventTime': event_time
                }
            )
            print(f"Successfully wrote {object_key} to DynamoDB")
    else:
        print("No 'Records' key found in the event.")
    
    return {'statusCode': 200}
Click Deploy button (orange)

Part D: Configure IAM Permissions
Step 1: Add DynamoDB Permission
Go to Lambda → S3ToDynamo function

Click Configuration tab

Click Permissions (left menu)

Click the Role name (blue link)

In IAM console, click Add permissions → Attach policies

Search for: AmazonDynamoDBFullAccess

Check the box → Click Add permissions

Step 2: Add S3 Permission (if needed)
Click Add permissions → Attach policies again

Search for: AmazonS3ReadOnlyAccess

Check the box → Click Add permissions

Step 3: Go Back to Lambda Function
Part E: Increase Lambda Timeout
Step 1: Update Timeout Settings
In Lambda function → Configuration tab

Click General configuration (left menu)

Click Edit

Timeout: Set to 0 minutes 30 seconds

Memory: Set to 256 MB (optional)

Click Save

Part F: Add S3 Trigger
Step 1: Add Trigger to Lambda
In Lambda function → Configuration tab

Click Triggers (left menu)

Click Add trigger

Select S3 from dropdown

Bucket: Select malleshaishu

Event types: PUT (or s3:ObjectCreated:Put)

Click Add

